    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/lUM5Z.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 52616,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 157247,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/157247/t-j-crowder",
                "reputation": 1081806,
                "display_name": "T.J. Crowder",
                "accept_rate": 91
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 4,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1383404611,
            "creation_date": 1383404611,
            "body": "<blockquote>\n  <p>...but I think there might be a security flaw in this approach. For instance, if the user accesses the application on a public wifi network (in a coffee shop, airport, hotel... whatever)...<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>Not just that. People who have wireless broadband in their home will all seem to be from the same IP, so if two people who live together both want to use your site simultaneously (maybe one recommended it to the other), they'll conflict.<\/p>\n\n<p>If you can't use cookies, you could use the old J2EE technique of putting the session ID in every URL. If you're already using J2EE, you can use its built-in support for this (<a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javaee/6/api/javax/servlet/http/HttpServletResponse.html#encodeURL%28java.lang.String%29\" rel=\"nofollow\"><code>HttpServletResponse#encodeURL<\/code><\/a> and such), which will use <code>;jsessionid=token<\/code> on the URL. If you aren't, it's simple enough to implement the technique using a query string parameter.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 19743254,
            "question_id": 19743217
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2f0d9dec16bae1e06552af55ddefc11f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 277416,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 571407,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/571407/jb-nizet",
                "reputation": 694302,
                "display_name": "JB Nizet",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1383404709,
            "creation_date": 1383404709,
            "body": "<p>The servlet API allows tracking sessions without cookies, using URL-rewriting (every URL pointing to the app in a given session will contain the session ID). This is automatic if you respect a few rules:<\/p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>always use <code>HttpServletResponse.encodeRedirectURL()<\/code> when redirecting<\/li>\n<li>always use <code>HttpServletResponse.encodeURL()<\/code> when generating a URL (for a link, image or whatever)<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n\n<p>Note that the JSTL's <code>&lt;c:url&gt;<\/code> calls <code>encodeURL()<\/code> for you.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 19743268,
            "question_id": 19743217
        }
